10	110	24	This chapter contains procedures for the inspection , repair and maintenance of wood decks and structures on wood - hulled ships and craft .
11	134	4	24.2 Wood decay .
12	138	4	24.2.1 Primary Causes .
13	142	18	Wood decay is caused by a fungus growth which breaks down the cell structure within the wood .
14	160	16	This fungus thrives in fresh water but its growth is significantly retarded by salt water .
15	176	19	Wood decay generally occurs in those spaces which are poorly ventilated and where fresh water has gained access .
16	195	18	Poor drainage , allowing fresh water to stand , even in small amounts , is particularly hazardous .
17	213	21	The primary causes of wood decay found in ships using wood for hulls , decking and structures are identified as :
18	234	30	a. Insufficient ventilation and air circulation especially in spaces plagued by dampness and high humidity ( i. e. , chill room platforms and areas around fresh water tanks ) .
19	264	12	b. Obstructed drainpipes , scuppers , limbers , and drain holes .
20	276	16	c. Uncaulked or poorly maintained deck seams , especially around plywood decking and Deckhouse areas .
21	292	7	d. Washing down with fresh water .
22	299	14	e. Depressions in the deck from sanding which allows fresh water to stand .
23	313	15	f. Leaking plumbing especially in heads , water closets , and food preparation areas .
24	328	3	24.2.2 Recognition .
25	331	15	Decay in the deck and hull structure is often concealed and hard to detect .
26	346	14	It is usually not recognizable by visible fungus except in joints between surfaces .
27	360	16	Decay may be suspected if paint coating is discolored or the wood surface is cupped .
28	376	11	The affected wood has a pronounced stringy , fibrous appearance .
29	387	26	Thoroughly decayed wood is brittle which , when dry , breaks easily across the grain with a distinct brash fracture and may crumble into powder .
30	413	23	Black stains spreading along the grain from ferrous metal fastenings are usually a result of chemical reactions instead of from decay fungi .
31	436	14	Testing procedures for suspected decay areas are detailed in reference ( a ) .
32	450	4	24.2.3 Preventive Measures .
33	454	11	Detailed preventive measures are described in reference ( a ) .
34	465	25	General preventive measures for the reduction of wood decay are identified in the following paragraphs , and should be accomplished by Ship ’s Force .
35	490	11	a. Correct or remove all interference with complete water runoff .
36	501	14	b. Repair fresh water leaks in plumbing drains and fresh water supply systems .
37	515	8	c. Maintain ventilation system in proper operation .
38	523	21	Ensure ventilation system filters are Kept clean , maintained clear of all foreign material , and ventilation terminals remain open .
39	544	21	d. Carefully caulk and maintain deck seams , especially around plywood decking , deckhouse , hull fittings and foundation areas .
40	565	16	e. In fair weather , open hatches and deck plates to supplement the air circulation .
41	581	15	f. Remove wet dunnage or shoring in below deck spaces and permit to dry .
42	596	8	g. Avoid washing down with fresh water .
43	604	10	Use only salt water due to its preservation Values .
44	614	28	h. Wash down the ship or craft with salt water following periods of inclement weather to eliminate fresh water and restore salt washed away by the rainfall .
45	642	7	i. Avoid heavy buildup of paint .
46	649	14	j. Check MCM bilges and accessible voids for standing fluids once each watch .
47	663	11	Identify and correct any leaks and promptly remove any fluids .
48	674	9	MCMs are designed to operate with dry bilges .
49	683	27	Prolonged contact with fluids will result in wood swell , which can lead to external glass reinforced plastic delamination , planking damage , and machinery misalignment .
50	710	4	24.2.4 Corrective Measures .
51	714	20	a. Treat new wood , used during new construction or in repaired areas , with a copper naphthenate preservative .
52	734	17	This product is produced in a clear and colorless form or in a bright green color .
53	751	24	The green preservative has a higher level of copper and is considered to be the more durable and efficient of the two preservatives .
54	775	37	If the treated wood is to be varnished , finished with light - colored paints or left bare , use the clear preservative since the green color will bleed through varnishes and light - colored paints .
55	812	33	b. Build up a heavy concentration of the preservative with a series of three or more heavy applications using a brush , spray or immersing the wood in a preservative filled tank .
56	845	21	On - going protection requires periodic application of the preservative to bare wood structures at about five - year intervals .
57	866	9	Wood treated on this basis will last indefinitely .
58	875	34	c. Early identification of decayed areas will allow damaged wood to be treated with an anti - decay product that will harden up the soft wood and prevent the further spread of decay .
59	909	25	The product , available commercially , is a two - part mixture with deep penetrating properties that fills wood pores with a capillary action .
60	934	64	d. Before a wood structure is so badly decayed that its replacement is necessary , a possible long lasting repair is made by drilling a series of 1 / 4 " to 3 / 8 " diameter holes in and around the affected areas and gravity feeding the anti - decay mixture in sufficient quantity to allow total penetration of the damaged area .
61	998	15	A guide for proper application of this product is provided with each repair kit .
62	1013	37	Avoid removing or disturbing bad wood during repairs , since the original wood , whether good or bad , serves as a container for the product and preserves the shape and size of the affected member .
63	1050	13	Initial curing of the product takes place about one hour after application .
64	1063	30	Total curing takes place after one week , at which time the treated wood resembles petrified wood and the growth of rot in the treated area is effectively stopped .
65	1093	13	Repairs should be accomplished by Ship ’s Force during regular maintenance periods .
66	1106	6	24.3 Deck and hull maintenance .
67	1112	4	24.3.1 Inspection Requirements .
68	1116	16	With reasonable care , wood - hulled ships can give many years of economical service .
69	1132	23	Make frequent inspections to detect any leaks beneath the covering board , around the deckhouse areas and seams in the deck planking .
70	1155	14	Reference ( a ) lists general maintenance requirements for wood - hulled ships .
71	1169	4	24.3.2 Maintenance Policies .
72	1173	13	Specific maintenance policies and repair practices are described in the following paragraphs .
73	1186	29	a. As a general policy , because of the ever present risk of decay developing beneath any wood coating , leave wood strip planked decks uncoated and unpainted .
74	1215	16	b. Limit the cleaning of wood decks to scrubbing with mild detergents and salt water .
75	1231	17	Never use fresh water for wash - downs since it encourages growth of decay producing fungi .
76	1248	14	Do not use strong detergents , acids , and bleaches for deck cleaning .
77	1262	5	Do not sand decks .
78	1267	18	c. Set up a routine of daily wetting down of wood strip planked decks with salt water .
79	1285	18	This wetting down causes strip deck planking to remain swollen and creates a tighter fit between planks .
80	1303	22	Wetting down is especially necessary during warm weather periods when the sun ’s heat will quickly dry out the deck planking .
81	1325	15	Do not allow water to accumulate in deck recesses for any length of time .
82	1340	21	d. Cover all plywood decks with a coating following the application and deck preparation procedures of reference ( b ) .
83	1361	30	e. Planking renewal will be approved by the TYCOM only on the basis of a technical survey that has positively shown specific need and complete justification for such renewal .
84	1391	17	Often used general terms such as " Rotten and Worn " are not considered sufficient justification .
85	1408	14	The technical basis for planking renewal must be formed in the following manner :
86	1422	24	( 1 ) Drill test bore holes in weather deck areas to find planking thickness in specific areas where plank wear is suspected .
87	1446	39	If the planking is not worn beyond the limits set forth in reference ( b ) , the planking will not be renewed unless other extenuating and justifiable circumstances dictate , and replacement is authorized by the TYCOM .
88	1485	14	( 2 ) Take boring plug samples of planking suspected of being decayed .
89	1499	7	Notify the TYCOM of inspection results .
90	1506	32	( 3 ) Once planking has reached the maximum wear limits ( found by bore test ) , the TYCOM will determine the need to replank or apply a deck coating .
91	1538	14	f. So far as practicable , repair deck leaks by recaulking deck seams .
92	1552	35	g. When deck planking wear limits have been reached , and other factors such as extensive deck leaks suggest use of a deck covering , a coating of polyurethane deck overlay may be used .
93	1587	25	Non - skid material must be Naval Sea Systems Command approved material compatible with the deck overlay as defined in reference ( b ) .
94	1612	19	h. Reset metallic planking fasteners when fastener heads are level with , or protrude above , deck level .
95	1631	26	Where the planking level is within 1 / 4 " or less of fastener head , filling with seam filler vice wooden plugging is authorized .
96	1657	24	Where bung plugs are installed , they must be set in black polyurethane seam filler per the requirements of reference ( c ) .
97	1681	22	i. Ships currently having polysulfide or polyurethane coated strip deck planking in good condition must continue to use the applied covering .
98	1703	18	Make minor repairs to this polyurethane coating as necessary using either a polysulfide or polyurethane repair kit .
99	1721	18	When the polysulfide covering is no longer economically repairable , replace it with a polyurethane type coating .
100	1739	16	Repairing cracks and holes in impervious deck coatings must be accomplished as soon as practical .
101	1755	13	Failure to do so will lead to deck rot and costly repairs .
