112	1911	8	24.3.5 Weather Deck or Planked Deck Repair .
113	1919	16	a. Remove all loose or decayed cotton or oakum caulking after removing all seam filler .
114	1935	34	In areas where caulking is found to be in good condition , set this material deeper into the seam opening , ensuring it is driven in solidly to make room for additional caulking .
115	1969	14	b. Small , tight seams will require a new single thread of cotton .
116	1983	18	The size of the seam in width and depth determines the amount of cotton or oakum required .
117	2001	32	Install sufficient cotton or oakum so that the level of the top of the caulking is 1 / 4 " to 3 / 8 " below the surface of the decking .
118	2033	9	This will allow room for the seam filler .
119	2042	36	c. Unless marine glue ( pitch ) is used as a seam filler , seal the surface of the caulked cotton or oakum with a special seam primer that is compatible with the seam filler .
120	2078	12	Do not use a rubber - type seam filler over oakum .
121	2090	35	d. Prime or fill newly caulked seams at the end of each day ’s caulking to keep moisture out of the caulking material and to protect the dry surface of the deck plank seams .
122	2125	27	e. Rubber type seam fillers that are installed in seams with a caulking gun must also be hand worked into the seam with a putty knife .
123	2152	13	This is necessary to eliminate air pockets and voids in the seam .
124	2165	17	Hand working of the seam filler must be in one single direction to avoid air pockets .
125	2182	5	24.3.6 Underwater Planking Repairs .
126	2187	12	a. The forward and after rabbet must receive a thorough inspection .
127	2199	30	The rabbet seam in the stern area is covered with an anchor chafe plate and is not available for inspection or repair unless the anchor chafe plate is removed .
128	2229	26	Slack or rotten caulking allows for infestation of marine burrowers and decay which , in the case of the rabbet seams forward , goes undetected .
129	2255	24	b. Inspect and test caulked plank seams covered with bottom sheathing for soundness whenever areas are exposed due to the removal of sheathing .
130	2279	21	In most cases , the seams have been covered for many years and have not been available for periodic maintenance .
131	2300	16	These seams , although covered with sheathing , do eventually waste away or become slack .
132	2316	20	The seams at the planking butts are more susceptible to slackening and erosion due to movement at the joints .
133	2336	17	Under normal conditions , it is necessary to recaulk these joints every 10 to 15 years .
134	2353	40	c. If the outer strand of oakum caulking appears to be satisfactory , then the seam may be repaired by setting the existing caulking deep into the seam and adding more strands of oakum to fill the seam depth .
135	2393	28	If the old caulking is wasted away or decayed , clean out the seam and remove all caulking and residue to make room for the new material .
136	2421	23	d. Before filling the newly caulked seam with a seam compound , paint the oakum and seam with anti - fouling paint .
137	2444	21	Painting the seam protects the oakum from marine burrowers and primes the wood in the way of the seam filler .
138	2465	22	Painting the oakum produces a hard surface finish which also makes a water barrier necessary for the protection of the oakum .
